  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Mausoleum of 1898
  author: Hong Ja-beon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I lost my mother's face when still nursing at her breast.
    Who could have known that lonely grave would rest upon this mountain?
    Though the underworld's path divides us, separating voice and form,
    Her love remains, still brightening the fabric of my remembrance.
    Among the overgrown grass, perhaps her spirit holds some knowing;
    On the thousand-li journey home, how can I hold back these tears?
    With ten thousand sorrows my words cannot contain,
    I set this poem upon the gentle flowing water to carry them away.
  footnotes:
    - The title refers to the year 1898 (Mausoleum of 1898 or a significant event in that year), likely marking the date of the mother's death or the occasion of this remembrance.
    - Colorful garments (彩衣 / 알락옷) are associated in East Asian tradition with filial piety and the memory of departed parents.
    - The image of entrusting the poem to flowing water reflects a classical motif of releasing one's sorrows into nature, allowing the natural world to bear witness to human grief.
